TI  - How to restrict informal recycling of photovoltaic modules: Research on closed-loop supply chain decision-making of photovoltaic modules under different recycling subsidy policies
AU  - Gao, Jiaming
AU  - Zhang, Li
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - Due to their advantages of low cost, the informal recycling channels of photovoltaic modules occupy over 60 % of the market share for recycling photovoltaic modules, and the unit recycling cost is only about 50 % of that of formal recycling channels. However, their non - standard operations not only result in resource waste, but also pose environmental pollution and safety hazards. This article establishes a long - term closed - loop supply chain that includes photovoltaic module manufacturers, photovoltaic module retailers, consumers, legitimate recyclers, and non-formal recyclers. Through a differential game model, it studies how recycling subsidy policies curb informal recycling of photovoltaic modules. The conclusions are as follows: (1) The government subsidy policy is highly effective in restricting informal recycling of photovoltaic modules. (2) The policy model offers significant differentiated benefits. (3) Both the size of the photovoltaic module recycling market and consumer price sensitivity influence recycling behavior, with market factors dominating recycling decisions. (4) Government regulatory tools can optimize the combi-nation strategy to deter-mine whether to focus on developing the recycling market or restricting the profits of informal recyclers.
